<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.familjenguild.com/dspMember.php?Name=Foxeous">Profile</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> : <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.familjenguild.com/dspCurrentNews.php">Familjen</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub27.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bemeni>Bemeni</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:green;'>Tavern Patron</span></span><br>  Posts: 189<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(1/30/03 10:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3093.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://sc.communities.msn.com/tn/86/30/Bemeni/1/190.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Way too much info...</span><hr size=1> I knew I was addicted when I saw how angry I would get when I couldn't play. When I preferred to honor my commitments to people in game over friends and family in real life. When I would lose sleep and go in late to work. When a day off meant spending it grinding. When I stopped answering the phone so I wouldn't have to hear my friends and family say &quot;Oh, you're playing that game again?&quot;. I notice that the more I play, the more I WANT to play. I looked at my phone bill and saw all the long distance calls to EQ people. When my personal life started getting crappier and crappier, I blamed EQ, the guild I was leading, the people I played with, even went as far as to hate Bemeni, as if she were real and the cause. <br>
<br>
Now I know these were MY shortcomings, and nothing else. EQ is once again what it should be in my life, just a game. I like to play, but I no longer log on automatically and stand around looking for something to do. I play now to spend time with some friends I made in EQ that I have been lucky enough to share something with that transcended the pixels we control.<br>
<br>
I don't think I will ever see Vex Thal, or even NToV, unless someone sends me screenshots. But I also know I will never have to cancel dinner plans to finish a raid, nor have to call guildmates on the phone to wake them up to make them log in ever again. <br>
<br>
I think we all want to feel like we are a success, to feel needed, and cool. It's easy in EQ to feel like a success..for a few minutes. Then the newness of your epic wears off, the shine on your BP dulls, and you are left wanting more. So you go get more. Remember your first piece of gear that you KNEW was UBER? Or that first named mob you killed? Or the first time you went into that scary dungeon? We then spend hours trying to recapture that first high feeling. I read that crack is an awesome high it's first time, but can never be repeated, yet you are driven to find it again. I feel that happens here in many cases.<br>
<br>
We all want to feel needed. Think of when people leave a guild. What are their reasons, barring specific instances? <br>
<br>
&quot;No one pays attention to me. No on groups with me. No one appreciates me&quot; (they want to feel needed)<br>
or<br>
&quot;I want to see the &quot;high end game&quot;&quot; or &quot;More loot&quot; (they want to feel successful) <br>
<br>
No, this doesn't even BEGIN to mean everyone. But I think we can all see some of this in ourselves, and in others around us.<br>
 <br>
I am still more attached to the game than I would like, as evidence in the fact I think about EQ when I am not playing, and come to boards like this one, but at least it's an improvment. <br>
<br>
Progress, not Perfection.  <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Bemeni Risingsoul<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><br>
Rockstar<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Mystic Valor's Token Chick<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Joyously Becoming</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub27.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kaedo>Kaedo</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://members.cox.net/~kaedo1/smicon.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:pink;'>Tavern Floor Sweeper</span></span><br>  Posts: 18<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(1/30/03 10:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3093.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I'm curious...</span><hr size=1> Anything in excess is harmful. You can drink too much water. Things become &quot;an addiction&quot; when you obsess about them. Even when you are not &quot;doing&quot; your addiction, you are planning and manipulating things in order to get more.<br>
<br>
There are more addicted people in this world than society would care to admit. I see a lot of my family who criticize the amount of time I spend playing EQ, but from my perspective, they are the teapot calling the kettle black. These people may spend hours a day in front of the television. Perhaps they work, and when they come home, they are still working. Perhaps they read, and read and read and read. Sometimes I get ill when I check my days played. But then you have to wonder... what if there was a days watching TV counter? Or a days spent in night-clubs counter? What would those reveal about people?<br>
<br>
More people are attached to things than they care to admit. Why? Perhaps because they are trying to forget that they are miserable and unhappy. Strangely enough, its these habits that prevent people from experiencing new things and growing, which is a fulfilling process in itself. And many people who are couch potatoes or work-a-holics or even alcoholics would be the first to admit that they need to get out more. So why do they continue to obsess? I think its due to fear.<br>
<br>
They are afraid of new challenges, perhaps fearing failure, perhaps fearing rejection, perhaps they are insecure. Why do I say these things? Because they are the reasons I had an addiction. Before EQ it was console games or single player games. But, as Bem hinted at: EQ kinda gives us a stage to look good in front of other real players and to win their acceptance, to experience friendship and make emotional bonds.<br>
<br>
EQ is almost a &quot;proxy&quot; world which we can hide our insecurities and act how we would act without fear. We can be BOLD and if we screw up, we just have to CR, or change guilds, or roll up a new character and try again. And if you are a kick ass Monk or Enchanter or whatever in EQ because you are acting without insecurity or fear, chances are you will value your time doing that rather than living IRL with insecurity. <br>
<br>
Living without fear or insecurity is an empowering feeling.<br>
<br>
This revelation is my personal experience at least. What I have done, is that I see the cool things Kaedo does, how he acts, and I try to integrate that into my real life. Now of course, if I do something risky enough IRL that I might die, I realize I am not going to return to my &quot;bind point.&quot; Nonetheless, Kaedo's prowess, attitude, and abilities come from his silent confidence--he has little or no insecurities to speak of. This silent confidence I am trying to integrate into the guy behind the keyboard. And its working. And its pretty awesome when I can manage to have that silent confidence.<br>
<br>
Some things are physical addictions, your body has withdrawals. Some addictions perhaps are mental.  However, I believe that some addictions are chosen, in order to escape what we would rather not admit to ourselves.  And perhaps these choices bring the true physical and mental addictions upon us. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">Kaedo Risingsoul</div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
