<br>
I'm curious as to whether you are inquiring as to short-term or long-term gaming addiction.  Most online games haven't been out longer than 3 years or so...unlike smoking or drinking or partaking in illegal drugs, which usually last much, much longer.  Most of us playing don't even think EQ will be be around in 5 years.  (Or, if it is, it will most likely be in a different media or a different game.)<br>
<br>
It doesn't take a lifetime to destroy one's real world relationships with an addiction to gaming, of course.  In some cases, even a few weeks is bad enough.  In other cases, spouses or g/b friends are still hoping and praying their loved ones come out of it after a few years.<br>
<br>
I've played video games since the days of Atarii and Intellivision.  I've purchased almost every system on the market at one time or another, from Nintendo (and SNES, and N64) to Sega (and Sega Genesis, and Sega CD), from 3DO (or whatever it was called, I think it was out all of 4 months.  Cartridges looked like a credit card.) to Playstation, PS2, Xbox, and the Game Cube.  I've played hundreds of games.  I always prefered role-playing games, but the problem with almost all of the games were that they were linear.  You went from A to B to C.  And they all ended after 40 or so hours of playing.  I watched friends play hour upon endless hour of mindless car racing, shooting, sports,  or fighting games...games with no real end, imho.  They just played and played.  <br>
<br>
I never understood how they could be content to play one game to the exclusion of all others, especially one where they couldn't win.<br>
<br>
Now I know.  EQ has the non-linear quality I've always searched for in a game.  It has people to interact with in a way console games never allowed.  It's a role playing game with monsters and fighting, and yet also tradeskills and honor and communication.<br>
<br>
Console games made video games a rather short-term addiction.  You could only do so much before you HAD to stop.  There wasn't any content left.  Your thumbs wore out.  The game gliched from an over-heated console.  The &quot;save&quot; battery in the cartridge was used up.  (I loved Might and Magic, *sniff*) Yet, even then, there were angry relations bitter over the power video games had on their loved ones.  Anyone remember the cartoon Gary (The Far Side) Larson did about parents wondering if saving Princess Zelda had any real-world applications?<br>
<br>
Addiction in gaming would also need to be defined.  How many hours a day makes it addictive? If you spend 3 hours?  8?  14?  Your average American spends 30 hours a week watching television.  If, instead, you played EQ, which is worse?  EQ, because it cuts you off from your family instead of allowing you to converse during commercials that try to tell you what to buy, think and do?  EQ at least makes you think and plan, whereas television would much rather you sit on your couch and mindlessly absorb the images they see fit for you.  So, if you spent time playing EQ rather than watching television, is that addiction?  Would you consider someone addicted to television if they watched as much TV as they played, if were 3 or 4 hours a night?  Would families be up in arms over it?<br>
<br>
I don't know.  I do know that almost every player I've met in the game takes RL breaks.  Sometimes for days, sometimes for months.  Sometimes they never come back at all.  I don't think there are more addicted players than there are non-addicted.  I would estimate 1 of a hundred or so.  By my own definion of addicted, by which I mean they can stop playing if they wish to.  If something comes up, or if they get bored, or if their families protest.  (Of course, I am in a guild where the charter states RL comes first.)  <br>
<br>
It is a rough estimate, of course.  I base it on people I see when I play.  There are a few people that I see day in, day out, at any hour.  But even they take breaks.  Many people, I see cycle through throughout the day.  Groups break up after a few hours because of RL commitments.  A person that needed something from me is offline an hour later.  The faces and names in the Bazaar and in other zones I frequent are different every day.  I still meet new people of my own level (65), which, if we were all addicted and played endlessly, we would probably know each other much better.  Sure, we do know a lot of people...but then, you don't get to 60 or 65 without a lot of interaction from a great many people.<br>
<br>
In conclusion, I'd say the others that have posted are correct.  Addiction, whether online games or smoking or drugs or whatever, usually comes from an addictive personality, not the game. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.familjenguild.com/dspMember.php?Name=Hildie"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.familjenguild.com/images/logo/hildie.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub27.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jehmgryphonkin>Jehm Gryphonkin</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:pink;'>Tavern Floor Sweeper</span></span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(1/30/03 10:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3093.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://claim.goldrush.com/~kmcclure/jehmicon2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I'm curious...</span><hr size=1> Well... addiction over any period of time i suppose.  And about online Games.  I guess what i'm trying to get to is whether or not online games are truely so addictive a thing that some people just cannot free themselves from it, period.  Not any game in particular, just online gaming in general. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub27.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=illuvatorbrightstar@thesaryrntavern>Illuvator Brightstar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:pink;'>Tavern Floor Sweeper</span></span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(1/30/03 10:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.s